<DocsLayout
  title="System Architecture"
  description="How ostk's primitives compose to solve the six problems running multiple AI agents creates: crash recovery, agent containment, verifiable history, write coordination, portable deployment, and observation without polling."
  sectionLabel="SECTION_01 // ARCHITECTURE"
  activeTab="architecture"
>
  <p class="font-headline text-lg text-on-surface-variant italic leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-12">
    Six problems show up the moment you put agents in front of a real codebase. ostk's architecture is the composition that solves them. Each section below names a problem, walks the composition that addresses it, and points at the primitives that compose.
  </p>

  <p class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-16">
    For the verb-by-verb surface, run <code class="text-primary">ostk help</code> or <code class="text-primary">ostk abi list</code>. For normative spec text, see <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-posix-kernel.md" class="text-primary hover:underline"><code>docs/spec/llmos-posix-kernel.md</code></a>. This page is the operator's reading guide — what composes into what.
  </p>

  <!-- Problem 01 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_01 // DAEMON_DIES_MID_TASK</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Your daemon crashes while an agent is working. What happens to the work?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Nothing is lost. ostk writes the audit ring (<code class="text-primary">.ostk/journal.jsonl</code>) as a write-ahead log; every turn boundary writes a drain snapshot of the agent's state. When the daemon comes back up, <code class="text-primary">fold(journal.jsonl)</code> replays the log and rehydrates each session from its last drain. The client reconnects on the same socket; from the agent's perspective, the disconnect was a long pause.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        <code class="text-primary">.ostk/journal.jsonl</code> (WAL) · drain snapshots · Connection Continuity (invariant X) · Anchor Exclusivity (VIII).
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/util/audit.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/serve/server.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/drain.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 02 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_02 // AGENT_TRIES_TO_ESCAPE</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">An agent gets creative and writes outside its lane. Then what?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Three layers compose. <strong class="text-on-surface">Pin caps</strong> deny by default at the tool layer — every <code class="text-primary">fs_ops</code> or <code class="text-primary">bash</code> call is checked before bytes hit disk. <strong class="text-on-surface">The OS sandbox</strong> (Landlock on Linux, Seatbelt on macOS) physically blocks writes outside allowed paths regardless of how the agent tries. <strong class="text-on-surface">Bypass detection</strong> flags any file that changed outside the kernel surface on next read. Tool-layer covers the expected path; the sandbox covers the escape path; bypass detection covers the unexpected. No single layer is load-bearing.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        <a href="/docs/pins" class="text-primary hover:underline">pin caps</a> · tool-layer interception · nono sandbox · bypass detection.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/serve/policy.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/sandbox.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/serve/tools/fs_ops.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 03 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_03 // PROVE_WHAT_SHIPPED</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">You need to prove what an agent did, not just trust the log.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      The audit chain isn't a log — it's the substrate's only truth. Every kernel-mediated action is an append-only event in <code class="text-primary">.ostk/journal.jsonl</code>, hash-chained against the previous row's signature. Each row is Ed25519-signed in-process at write time using the operator's identity key (no GPG subprocess, no signing latency). Replay reconstructs identical state byte-for-byte. The daemon is a cache; the journal is the ledger.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        WAL append → hash chain (<code class="text-primary">prev_hash</code>) → Ed25519 sign (<code class="text-primary">sig</code>) → replay reconstructs state. Owned State (II) makes the writer unique; Anchor Exclusivity (VIII) keeps two daemons from forking the chain.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/util/audit.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/signing.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 04 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_04 // TWO_AGENTS_ONE_FILE</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Two agents edit the same file at the same time. Who wins?</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      The second writer always sees the conflict. Every file carries a generation counter in <code class="text-primary">.ostk/gen_table.jsonl</code>. Edits are compare-and-swap: the agent declares the counter it read; if another agent has bumped it, the write fails loudly with a diff. For non-overlapping edits, Hot PR auto-merges; for overlapping edits, the second agent re-reads and re-tries. Nothing disappears between you and what your agents actually did.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        gen_table generation counters · OCC compare-and-swap · Hot PR three-tier merge · Path AND Handle (V) makes the file uniquely addressable to both readers.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/cas.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/hotpr.rs</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/serve/tools/fs_ops.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 05 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_05 // SHIP_TO_SOMEONE_ELSE</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">You want to hand your agent setup to a different operator and have it just run.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      <code class="text-primary">application/v1</code> packages an agent system as a content-addressed, signed directory with declared capabilities, supervisor trees, and a manifest of claims. The receiving operator runs <code class="text-primary">ostk app install</code>; the substrate validates the signature, registers the capability declarations, and the supervisor starts. The application's runtime existence IS its slice of the claim graph keyed by <code class="text-primary">(app_id, install_id, start_id)</code>. When the run finishes, the original publisher can verify what happened against the audit chain the receiving operator publishes.
    </p>
    <p class="font-body text-xs text-outline italic max-w-xl mb-4">
      "I can hand you my application as a signed file. You install it. You start it. It runs. When it finishes, I can verify what happened against the audit chain you publish." — application/v1 §1
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        application/v1 manifest · Ed25519 attestation · claim-graph lifecycle (9 ratified schemas) · capability declarations · supervisor restart strategies.
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-application.md" class="text-primary hover:underline"><code>docs/spec/llmos-application.md</code></a> v0.1, <code class="text-primary">src/commands/app/</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Problem 06 -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">PROBLEM_06 // SEE_EVERYTHING_WITHOUT_POLLING</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">You want to see what every agent did, in real time, without writing pollers or running queries.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      The kernel writes the audit ring; indexers tap it as logical-decoding subscribers (Postgres-style); projections land at stable paths in a VFS namespace. You query a directory listing, not a log. <code class="text-primary">cat /fleet/proc</code> gives you the live process table; <code class="text-primary">ls /needles</code> gives you open work; every projection rebuilds from journal replay if it goes stale. No polling, no replication, no separate truth source.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-surface-container-low p-5 max-w-xl mb-3">
      <div class="font-label text-[10px] text-primary mb-2">COMPOSES_FROM</div>
      <div class="font-body text-xs text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        audit ring (WAL) · indexer subscribers in <code class="text-primary">dispatch::fire</code> · VFS namespace projections · forthcoming <code class="text-primary">kernel::registry</code> typed read API (EPIC →1652).
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-outline max-w-xl">
      Source: <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-observation-substrate.md" class="text-primary hover:underline"><code>docs/spec/llmos-observation-substrate.md</code></a>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/graph/indexer/</code>, <code class="text-primary">src/kernel/vfs/namespace.rs</code>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The composition itself -->
  <section class="mb-16">
    <div class="section-label mb-4">THE_COMPOSITION</div>
    <h2 class="serif-text text-3xl font-medium text-on-surface mb-4">Six problems, one shape.</h2>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      Each answer above is two or three primitives composed against a clear failure mode. The kernel makes the composition mechanically possible — bounded waits, owned state, dead-process reaping, namespace isolation, handle uniqueness, anchor exclusivity, connection continuity, and four others (the ten invariants). The substrate makes the kernel queryable. The daemon makes it long-lived. The ABI makes it agent-callable. Drivers extend it. <code class="text-primary">application/v1</code> makes it portable.
    </p>

    <p class="font-body text-sm text-secondary leading-relaxed max-w-xl mb-4">
      What you don't have to know: which file holds which counter, which subsystem listens on which signal, which invariant is implemented in which phase. Those live in the kernel and the spec. The architecture is the composition story above; the rest is implementation.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-px bg-surface-variant max-w-2xl">
      <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-posix-kernel.md" class="bg-surface-container-high p-4 hover:bg-surface-container transition-colors">
        <div class="font-body text-xs text-primary font-bold mb-1">→ KERNEL_SPEC (NORMATIVE)</div>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-secondary">The ten invariants in full normative form. RFC 2119 keywords. Phase-by-phase rollout map.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-observation-substrate.md" class="bg-surface-container-high p-4 hover:bg-surface-container transition-colors">
        <div class="font-body text-xs text-primary font-bold mb-1">→ OBSERVATION_SUBSTRATE (NORMATIVE)</div>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-secondary">Audit ring, subscriber dispatch, VFS namespace contract.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/haystack/blob/main/docs/spec/llmos-application.md" class="bg-surface-container-high p-4 hover:bg-surface-container transition-colors">
        <div class="font-body text-xs text-primary font-bold mb-1">→ APPLICATION_V1 (NORMATIVE)</div>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-secondary">Signed manifest schema, claim graph, supervisor vocabulary, lifecycle verbs.</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/mcp" class="bg-surface-container-high p-4 hover:bg-surface-container transition-colors">
        <div class="font-body text-xs text-primary font-bold mb-1">→ MCP (BOTH DIRECTIONS)</div>
        <p class="font-body text-[10px] text-secondary">Inbound bridge for external clients; outbound proxy for ostk-driven agents.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

